Mystery solved: That's why we cannot tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from being able to tickle themselves. Scientists at the Humboldt University in Berlin found out with the help of experiments on rats, as they said on Thursday evening. Progress had also been made on the question of why children defend themselves so fiercely against tickling, only to demand more.
Finally, it has also become shown why the approach of a tickling hand alone triggers laughter before the touch. This is due to a deep layer in the cerebrum, which triggers laughter even in the expectation of tickling.
According to the data, earlier research has shown that rats react with " laughter " in the ultrasound range when they are tickled by humans. This " laughter " is mediated by the part of the cerebral cortex that serves the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-touch
Until now, it had been assumed that the brain could distinguish between self-contact and touch by others - that is, why humans cannot tickle themselves. However, the Berlin researchers have now found out in the experiments on the rats that laughter as well as the activity of the respective area of the cerebral cortex are suppressed during self-contact. This was also the case when living beings clean themselves. However, during the foreign contact and the tickling by the scientists, the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh had been intensified.
However, if self-contact and contact by others happen at the same time, laughter is also suppressed. This indicates that the brain of the rat cannot distinguish between self-contact and contact by others. The new findings suggested that people cannot tickle themselves because self-touch activates a brake in the cerebrum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves. Accordingly, they sometimes broke off this initiation prematurely in the experiment, showed flight behavior or rigidity of terror. This ambivalence resemto the behavior of the children. The ambivalence of tickling was a behavioural reaction that was the same in rats and humans.
