Study on causes of heart disease
Smoking, obesity, an unhealthy diet - there are risk factors for cardiovascular diseases. But what really triggers a heart failure or an infarction? Researchers in Hamburg now want to take a close look at the genetic material of 9,000 healthy and sick people.
By analysing the genetic ome of 9,000 people, Hamburg and Swiss scientists want to find out the causes of cardiovascular diseases in more detail.
The research project is the largest of its kind in the German-speaking world, the University Hospital Center Hamburg-Eppendorf (UKE) announced on Friday. The Kühne Foundation is funding the project with 12.5 million euros. From Switzerland, the Davos High Mountain Clinic, which is owned by the Foundation, and the University Hospital Zurich are involved.
Obesity, smoking and an unhealthy diet are among the main risk factors for cardiovascular diseases that can be influenced. Genetic factors help determine the risk. However, the interaction between genes and external influences is insufficiently known, it was said. Now, the scientists want to compare the complete genetic material of 8,000 healthy people with that of 1000 former patients of the University Cardiovascular Centre at the UKE.
According to the hospital, possible disease causing changes in DNA - so-called mutations - are currently known in more than 4,000 of the approximately 20,000 relevant human genes. Approximately 200 are added every year.
According to the initiators, the aim of the five-year project is to develop new options for the prevention, detection and treatment of cardiac arrhythmias, heart failure and heart attacks. According to Stefan Blankenberg, head of the University Cardiovascular Center, the data could also be used for research into other common diseases. New findings into the interaction between heart and brain, heart and kidney as well as on cancer are possible.
The chairman of the Kühne Foundation, Klaus-Michael Kühne (82), also emphasized that there was a firm will to use the data for research into other diseases. So far, the Foundation's clinic in Davos has primarily treated allergies. Now, a Center for Cardiovascular Precision Medicine should be established on the local medical campus and a professorfor for bioinformatics is created. To justify his commitment, the Swiss-based logistics entrepreneur said that he had been open-heart operated in Hamburg three years ago and was very grateful.
The biosamples of the healthy participants come from Hamburgers, who also participate in the " Hamburg City Health Study. " According to the hospital, this is the largest local health study in the world with 45,000 test persons. The scientists assured that the genetic deccoding of genetic genetic genetic is strictly paid to the protection of anonymised data. It is one petabyte (1000 terabytes) of data, said Holger Moch from the University Hospital Zurich.
According to the UKE, the genetic material of a human being can be decoded within 24 hours. The pure material costs for this would be 1300 euros. The first gene sequencing worldwide, the results of which were published in 2001, has cost several hundred million euros. The study is to begin on 1 October, and all 9,000 samples are to be analysed by the end of 2020. Initial results are expected in the following year.
