Attention: Smartphone NEVER wirelessly
Practical but harmful
Inductive technology via Qi standard is extremely practical, but should not be used.
Since several new smartphones have recently come onto the market that support wireless charging and sell very well - above all the new iPhone 11 models, we would like to recall a study from the beginning of July. Wireless charging of mobile devices is extremely practical, but not necessarily recommendable.
Higher temperature increases battery
Researchers warn against wireless charging charging of smartphones. According to the findings of the University of Warwick, this is extremely harmful for the devices. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat generation. If a mobile phone is charged normally by cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees within three hours. During wireless charging, however, have always measured above 30 degrees, even if the smartphone is perfectly aligned of alignsmartphone on the charging pad. If the mobile phone is slightly next to the coil, the temperature rises even higher. In addition, the wattage of the charging pad increases, which in turn drives up power consumption.
Capacity
According to the researchers, the temperature is a decisive factor for the durability of batteries. Every single degree plays a role here. When charging with higher temperatures, the battery not only loses capacity, but also does not last so long overall. Thus, the service life is lower. Therefore, the researchers advise to always charge the smartphone by cable. Since battery replacement on modern smartphones is always associated with high high costs, this should be a helpful tip. Apple has recently increased the costs of a battery replacement even more - for all iPhones.

The technology is extremely convenient: Simply place the device on a corresponding charging pad - these are now already installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without annoying cable clutter and laborious plug-dle. Since Qi (stands for inductive energy transmission) is a worldwide standard, in which even Apple participates, there are hardly any restrictions. Nevertheless, according to the researchers, the technology should only be used in exceptional cases.
