Comet crossed by another star
Astronomers are currently observing a comet from the depths of space. This has been achieved before. The comet allows conclusions to be drawn about other solar systems.
What was initially only a guess is now confirmed: an interstellar guest crosses through our solar system. The comet from the depths of space was named 2I / Borisov after its discoverer and has aroused the interest of astronomers all over the world.
The widely travelled comet was discovered on 30 August by amateur astronomer Gennady Borisov at the Margo Observatory in Crimea - with a self-made telescope of 65 centimetres in diameter. Follow-up observations from various observatories not only confirmed that it was an unknown comet, but also showed that it did not originate from our solar system.
After 1I /' Oumuamua in 2017, 2I / Borisov is only the second interstellar object that has been sighted during a flight of our solar system.
2I / Borisov offers astronomers the rare opportunity to gain close-up insights into a foreign solar system before it disappears never. Initial observations show that the interstellar comet is similar to those of our own system, as reported by by the Canary Asthysihysical Institute. " The current speed of the comet is high, about 150,000 kilometers per hour, which at this distance is well above the typical speeds rates of objects orbiting the Sun, " Davide Farnoccchia of the US space agency Nasreported in a statement.
According to the analyses, the comet is on a so-called hyperbola orbit, which takes it out of our system - and clearly of interstellar origin, as the International Astronomical Union (IAU) reported. It is also responsible for naming and categorization of celestial bodies. In honor of its discoverer, interstellar tail star, which was initially listed under catalogue number C / 2019 Q4, was given the designation 2I / Borisov, the first part of the name indicating that it is the second interstellar object discovered in our solar system.
The astronomers are lucky: in contrast to 1I /' Oumuamua, 2I / Borisov has already been seen in the approach, leaving the researchers have many months to investigate. " The object will reach its highest brightness in mid-December and then be visible with medium-sized telescopes until April 2020, " explained Farnocchia. " Therethat, it will only be observed with larger, professional telescopes by October 2020. "
Several observatories have already targeted the visitor. A team led by Karen Meech from the University of Hawaii, who had already led the characterization of 1I /' Oumuamua, determined the diameter of the celestial object for 2 to 16 kilometers in a first study. Images from the Gemini Observatory in Hawaii show a clear tail of the comet.
Researchers at the Astrophysical Institute of the Canary Islands (IAC) have already obtained a first so-called spectrum from the interstellar tail star, which offers a kind of fingerprint of its chemical composition. " The spectrum of this object is similar to that of comets in our solar system, and this indicates that its composition must be similar, " reported IAC researcher Julia de León. This observation suggests that comets in other solar systems could form through similar similar to those in ours, added de León's colleague Javier Licandro.
According to the IAU, the discovery of two interstellar visitors within just two years indicates that these objects could open up a new way to investigate certain processes in other solar systems. However, it is still difficult to estimate how often such visits. One of the next interstellar visitors could possibly intercept by a planned satellite mission by the European Space Agency Esa.
