Half of Europe's tree species are threatened with extinction
In addition to pests, diseases, alien species, unsustainable logging and the growth of cities are also causes of the threat, reported the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) in Brussels on Friday. It examined the stocks of all 454 tree species known in Europe. 265 of them do not occur on any other continent. Of these 265 58 percent are threatened. 66 are already at the highest level of endangerment and thus at the verge of extinction.
The IUCN classifies endangered species into six categories: from " potentially endangered " to " endangered, " " endangered, " " endangered " and " extinct in nature " to " extinct. " In total, it lists more than 28,000 animal and plant species worldwide as endangered.
rowan and chestnut threatened
In Germany, rowans (Sorbus) are particularly threatened, one of the authors, David Allen, told the German Press Agency. " Most are threatened because the populations are small anyway or by the transformation or weakening of their habitats. "
It also looks bad for the wild common horse chestnuts. They are regarded as " endangered " since 2017, level two on the IUCN scale. The biggest threat next to a fungus is the Balkan miner's moth. It has been spreading from Southeast Europe over the whole continent since the 1980s and has hardly any natural enemies. IUCN estimates the number of wild horse chestnuts (Aesculus hippocastanum) in Europe at less than 10,000 specimens. The trees in cities, parks and avenues are not considered in this assessment.
Shrub species and mosses also in danger
At the same time, the IUCN scientists compiled new European red lists for molluscs, shrubs and mosses. More than a fifth of molluscs and mosses and almost half of all shrub species are threatened, according to the IUCN. This is mainly due to the destruction of the wild, introduced species, agricultural practices and climate change. Molluscs such as snails played a key role in recycling nutrients in the soil and are an important food source for birds and other animals.
" This report shows that the situation is precarious for many overlooked and underestimated species, species that form the backbone of the European ecosystem and contribute to a healthy planet, " said Luc Bas, IUCN Director of the European Office. " We need to limit the impact of humans on our ecosystems and make the protection of these species a priority. "
