Influencer wants free upgrade: Lifelong flight ban at Cathay
Allegedly, Jaqueline Ng had been promised an upgrade by e-mail from Cathay Pacific. However, when she asked for it at check-in, she was not allowed to board - and she should never be allowed to fly with Cathay again.
Spontaneously get an upgrade for Business Class - many passengers dream of that. Sometimes they are lucky and the check-in staff offer a change from Economy Class for free.
However, this case shows how not to do it: A self-proclaimed influencer has actively asked the airline Cathay Pacific for a free upgrade. More than 65,000 users follow Jaqueline Ng on Instagram. On May 30th, it flew from Taiwan to New York and back on June June.
On the outward flight, employees refused to upgrade Jaqueline, even though she showed an e-mail in which Cathay Pacific allegedly promised an upgrade. The influencer claims to have received the letter from a marketing employee of the airline, while the airline accuses Jaqueline of falsifying the mail.
On the return flight, Jaqueline tried again to get an upgrade for the long-haul flight. This time, the woman is said to have shown the same mail, but with a different reference number. The employees at JFK airport were skeptical: They checked at the head office. And indeed, the employee from whom the mail allegedly comes, is said to have denied the mail contact with Jaqueline. This was also confirmed by the mail system, in which the messages did not appear.
The airline employees at the airport canceled Jaqueline's ticket and imposed a lifelong flight ban with Cathay Pacific. She had to buy a new flight tick to Taiwan for 1,400 US dollars (around 1,280 euros).
With her case, the influencer turned to Elliot Advocacy, a company that represents consumer interests. Cathay had reimbursed her for the price for her original ticket, Jaqueline also reimbursed the cost of the new ticket.
But as long as Jaqueline does not submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: For Cathay, the influencer has committed fraud, she remains blocked for future flights. Furthermore, the airline's terms and conditions state that it does not have to pay for the new flight. Jaqueline does not want to be satisfied with this - and is now hiring a lawyer.
Oil prices fall according to ceasefire report in Yemen
Oil prices fell by more than a dollar within a very short time on Friday. Recently, a barrel (159 litres) of the North Sea variety Brent cost 61.83 US dollars - about 1.4 percent less than the day before. The price of a barrel of the American variety West Texas Intermediate (WTI) fell by 1.3 percent to 55.77 dollars.
The slide was triggered by a Wall Street Journal report on a ceasefire in Yemen. Saudi Arabia is said to have agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
A drone attack on the oil facilities in Saudi Arabia in mid-September had brought five percent of global oil production to a standstill. Iran's Houthis rebels allied with Iran in the civil war country of Yemen had claimed for the attacks. Saudi Arabia, like the US government, blames Iran. A ceasefire would defuse the political tension in the region.
If an agreement is actually reached, one could focus on growth and demand worries, Ole Hansen, head of the commodity strategy department at Saxo Bank, told Bloomberg news agency.
Oil prices thus continue their downward movement over the past few days. A week ago, a barrel of WTI oil had cost up to almost $59, Brent almost $65.
Most recently, Bloomberg had reported, citing Insiders, that the repair work on oil plants in Saudi Arabia is progressing faster than expected after the attack in mid-September. Accordingly, the production volume has again reached a volume of eight million barrels per day and is moving back towards the original quantity.
Recently, there have been several press reports citing insiders reporting rapid progress by the state-owned oil company Saudi Aramco in the repair work. However, commodity experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning an IPO and wants to avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, there was some relaxation in the conflict between Iran and Western countries: the British oil tanker " Stena Impero " is on its way to leaving the port more than two months after the arrest by Iran and the recently granted release. The crew is now preparing the departure while the ship is still at anchor, shipping manager Erik Hånell told the Swedish radio in an SMS on Friday morning.
However, the US announced that it would move defensive missiles and soldiers to Iran Iranian arch-enemy in Saudi Arabia. Fear of an escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries such as the US and the UK had at times pushed up oil prices in recent weeks.
